e=\"whitburn\">{{cite book|last=Whitburn|first=Joel|title=Hot Country Songs 1944 to 2008|publisher=Record Research, Inc|year=2008|page=361|isbn=0-89820-177-2}}</ref>\n\nThom Jurek of [[Allmusic]] rated the album three stars out of five, saying that it \"isn't a perfect record, but it's a sincere one.\"<ref>{{cite web|url={{Allmusic|class=album|id=r822353|pure_url=yes}}|title=''Water & Bridges'' review|last=Jurek|first=Thom|work=Allmusic|accessdate=27 September 2010}}</ref>\n\n\"[[Someone Somewhere Tonight]]\" was later covered by [[Pam Tillis]] and [[Kellie Pickler]], the latter of which release the song as a single to country radio in May 2013. \"Half a Man\" was originally recorded by [[Anthony Smith (singer)|Anthony Smith]] on his album ''[[If That Ain't Country]]'', and his version charted at number 40 on [[Hot Country Songs]] in 2003. The title track was originally recorded by [[Collin Raye]] on his 2000 album ''[[Tracks (Collin Raye album)|Tracks]]'', which was also produced by Dann Huff.\n\n==Track listing==\n{{tracklist\n|title1 = Water & Bridges\n|writer1 = [[Tim Nichols]], [[Craig Wiseman]]\n|length1 = 4:09\n|title2 = Someone Is Me\n|writer2 = [[Josh Kear]], Joe Doyle\n|length2 = 3:30\n|title3 = [[Someone Somewhere Tonight]]\n|writer3 = Davis Raines, Walt Wilkins\n|length3 = 5:18\n|title4 = [[I Can't Unlove You]]\n|writer4 = Wade Kirby, Will Robinson\n|length4 = 3:24\n|title5 = Calling Me |note5 = duet with [[Don Henley]]\n|writer5 = Wiseman, Annie Roboff\n|length5 = 3:59\n|title6 = Half a Man\n|writer6 = [[Anthony Smith (singer)|Anthony Smith]]\n|length6 = 3:18\n|title7 = I Can Feel You Drifting\n|writer7 = [[Billy Kirsch]], Bat McGrath\n|length7 = 3:51\n|title8 = The Last Ten Years (Superman)\n|writer8 = Tommy Conners, [[D. Vincent Williams]]\n|length8 = 3:42\n|title9 = You'll Know Love\n|writer9 = [[Marc Beeson]], Don Pfrimmer, [[Mike Reid (singer)|Mike Reid]]\n|length9 = 4:13\n|title10 = My Petition\n|writer10 = [[Ashley Gorley]], Wade Kirby, Bryant Simpson\n|length10 = 4:12\n|title11 = One Life\n|writer11 = Beeson, [[Tim Johnson (songwriter)|Tim Johnson]]\n|length11 = 3:44\n}}\n\n==Personnel==\n{{div col}}\n* [[Kenny Rogers]] \u2013 lead vocals\n* [[John Barlow Jarvis]] \u2013 [[acoustic piano]] (1-6, 8-11)\n* Charlie Judge \u2013 [[Keyboard instrument|keyboards]] (2, 4, 5, 8), [[synthesizer]] (7)\n* Jim Hoke \u2013 [[accordion]] (5)\n* Warren Hartman \u2013 synthesizer (7)\n* [[Gordon Mote]] \u2013 acoustic piano (7)\n* [[Tom Bukovac]] \u2013 [[electric guitar]] (1, 3, 5, 6, 8-11)\n* [[Dann Huff]] \u2013 electric guitar (1-11)\n* [[Bryan Sutton]] \u2013 [[acoustic guitar]] (1, 3, 5, 6, 9, 10, 11)\n* Russ Pahl \u2013 [[steel guitar]] (1-10)\n* [[Kenny Greenberg]] \u2013 electric guitar (2, 7)\n* [[Biff Watson]] \u2013 acoustic guitar (2, 4, 7, 8)\n* [[Jonathan Yudkin]] \u2013 [[mandolin]] (2), [[bouzouki]] (4), [[fiddle]] (4, 8), cello (7), viola (7), violin (7), string arrangements and composing (7)\n* [[Bruce Bouton]] \u2013 [[dobro]] (8), steel guitar (11)\n* [[Michael Rhodes (musician)|Michael Rhodes]] \u2013 [[bass guitar]] (1, 3, 5, 6, 9, 10, 11)\n* [[Giant (band)|Mike Brignardello]] \u2013 bass guitar (2, 4, 7, 8)\n* [[Matt Chamberlain]] \u2013 [[drums]] (1, 3, 5, 6, 9, 10, 11)\n* [[Shannon Forrest]] \u2013 drums (2, 4, 7, 8)\n* [[Eric Darken]] \u2013 [[percussion]] (1, 3, 5, 6, 9, 10, 11)\n* [[Paul Buckmaster]] \u2013 string arrangements and conductor (1, 11)\n* [[London Philharmonic Orchestra|The London Session Orchestra]] \u2013 [[string instrument|strings]] (1, 11)\n* Perry Coleman \u2013 backing vocals (1, 2, 4-8, 10, 11)\n* Russell Terrell \u2013 backing vocals (2, 4, 6, 8, 10)\n* [[Sarah Buxton]] \u2013 backing vocals (3)\n* [[Don Henley]] \u2013 lead vocals (5)\n* [[Vince Gill]] \u2013 backing vocals (9)\n{{div col end}}\n\n==Production==\n* Producer \u2013 Dann Huff\n* Production Coordination \u2013 Mike \"Frog\" Griffith\n* A&R Coordination \u2013 Darrell Griffith\n* Recorded by Jeff Balding, Jedd Hackett, Mark Hagen and Justin Niebank.\n* Assistant Recording by Drew Bollman, Steve Crowder, Travis Daniels, Allen Ditto, Greg Lawrence and David Robinson.\n* Recorded at Blackbird Studios, Emerald Entertainment and Cartee Day Studios (Nashville, TN); Tree Sound Studios (Atlanta, GA).\n* Strings on Tracks 1 & 11 recorded by Steve Churchmeyer at [[Capitol Studios]] (Hollywood, CA), assisted by Aaron Walk.\n* Don Henley's vocal recorded by Mark Hagen at Patchwerk Recording Studio (Atlanta, GA).\n* Digital Editing \u2013 Christopher Rowe\n* [[ProTools|ProTools Engineer]] \u2013 Andy Ackland\n* Mixed by Justin Niebank at The Sound Kitchen (Franklin, TN); assisted by Drew Bollman and Melissa Mattey.\n* Mastered by Adam Ayan at Gateway Mastering (Portland, ME).\n* Art Direction \u2013 Joanna Carter\n* Design \u2013 Joe Rogers\n* Art Production \u2013 Denise Arguijo and Michelle Hall\n* Digital Imaging \u2013 Colourworks\n* Photography \u2013 Melanie Dunea\n\n==Chart performance==\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n! Chart (2006)\n! Peak<br />position\n|-\n| U.S. ''Billboard'' Top Country Albums\n| align=\"center\"| 5\n|-\n| U.S. ''Billboard'' 200\n| align=\"center\"| 14\n|}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n{{Kenny Rogers}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Water and Bridges}}\n[[Category:2006 albums]]\n[[Category:Capitol Records albums]]\n[[Category:albums arranged by Paul Buckmaster]]\n[[Category:Albums produced by Dann Huff]]\n[[Category:Kenny Rogers albums]]\n", "name_user": "Kaltenmeyer", "label": "safe", "comment": "clean up,typo(s) fixed: 4-8 \u2192 4\u20138", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Water_%26_Bridges"}
{"title_page": "Food Federation Germany", "text_new": "{{Infobox Organization\n|name                = Food Federation Germany\n|logo                = Food Federation Germany logo.svg\n|image               = \n|size                = \n|caption             = \n|abbreviation        = \n|formation           = 1955\n|status              = [[Non-profit organization|Non-profit organisation]]\n|purpose             = Trade body representing the German food sector ''from farm to fork''\n|location            = Claire-Waldoff-Stra\u00dfe 7, 10117 Berlin, Germany<br/>\nAvenue des Nerviens, 9-31, 1040 Brussels, Belgium\n|region_served       = Germany \n|membership          = German food trade associations, German food businesses, laboratories, law firms, individual members\n|leader_title        = President\n|leader_name         = Philipp Hengstenberg\n|main_organ          = Board\n|parent_organization = \n|affiliations        = \n|budget              = \n|website             = [https://www.lebensmittelverband.de/en/ Food Federation Germany]\n}}\n\n'''Food Federation Germany''' ([[German language|German]]: ''Lebensmittelverband Deutschland'') is the leading association of the German [[food industry|food sector]], representing the [[Agricultural value chain|food value chain]] in [[Germany]] ''from farm to fork'', i.e., from [[agriculture]], [[food manufacturing]], [[Craft|food craft]] and [[Retail|food retail]] to [[gastronomy]].<ref>Food Federation Germany: [https://www.lebensmittelverband.de/en/federation/about-us About us].</ref> The association operates offices in [[Berlin]], Germany, as well as [[Brussels]], Belgium.\n\n== Membership ==\nThe association's membership includes some 70 associations, 250 companies \u2013 ranging from mid-sized firms to international corporations \u2013, as well as 150 organizational and individual members.\n\nThe association itself is a member of the European food industry body [[FoodDrinkEurope]]<ref>[[FoodDrinkEurope]]: [https://www.fooddrinkeurope.eu/member/Lebensmittelverband-Deutschland/ Food Federation Germany (Lebensmittelverband)]</ref> as well as of [[European Movement Germany]].\n\n== History ==\n[[File:Federation for Food Law and Food Science logo.svg|thumb|160px|Federation for Food Law and Food Science logo]]\nFood Federation Germany was founded on March 10, 1955 in [[Nuremberg]], Germany, under the name ''Federation for Food Law and Food Science'' (German: ''Bund f\u00fcr Lebensmittelrecht und Lebensmittelkunde'', abbreviated ''BLL'') as a re-establishment of the ''Federation of German Food Manufacturers and Traders'' (German: ''Bund Deutscher Nahrungsmittel-Fabrikanten und -H\u00e4ndler'') that had been active from 1901 to 1945.<ref>Food Federation Germany: ''[https://www.lebensmittelverband.de/de/verband/historie History]'' (in German).</ref> In May 2019, the association's general meeting voted for changeing the association's name to ''Food Federation Germany'' (German: ''Lebensmittelverband Deutschland'').<ref>Food Federation Germany (9 May 2019): [https://www.lebensmittelverband.de/en/news/20190509-philipp-hengstenberg-is-president-of-new-food-federation-germany Philipp Hengstenberg is president of new \"Food Federation Germany\"]''</ref> The name change came into force in July 2019, followed by a rebranding process that was awarded a ''Rebrand 100: merit'' at the ''2020 Rebrand 100 Global Awards''.<ref>Rebrand.com: [https://rebrand.com/merit-food-federation-germany/ Food Federation Germany. 2020 REBRAND 100: merit].''</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* [https://www.lebensmittelverband.de/en/ Food Federation Germany's English website]\n\n[[Category:Food industry trade groups]]\n[[Category:1955 establishments in Germany]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox Organization\n|name                = Food Federation Germany\n|logo                = Food Federation Germany logo.svg\n|image               = \n|size                = \n|caption             = \n|abbreviation        = \n|formation           = 1955\n|status              = [[Non-profit organization|Non-profit organisation]]\n|purpose             = Trade body representing the German food sector ''from farm to fork''\n|location            = Claire-Waldoff-Stra\u00dfe 7, 10117 Berlin, Germany<br/>\nAvenue des Nerviens, 9-31, 1040 Brussels, Belgium\n|region_served       = Germany \n|membership          = German food trade associations, German food businesses, laboratories, law firms, individual members\n|leader_title        = President\n|leader_name         = Philipp Hengstenberg\n|main_organ          = Board\n|parent_organization = \n|affiliations        = \n|budget              = \n|website             = [https://www.lebensmittelverband.de/en/ Food Federation Germany]\n}}\n\n'''Food Federation Germany''' ([[German language|German]]: ''Lebensmittelverband Deutschland'') is the leading association of the German [[food industry|food sector]], representing the [[Agricultural value chain|food value chain]] in [[Germany]] ''from farm to fork'', i.e., from [[agriculture]], [[food manufacturing]], [[Craft|food craft]] and [[Retail|food retail]] to [[gastronomy]].<ref>Food Federation Germany: [https://www.lebensmittelverband.de/en/federation/about-us About us].</ref> The association operates offices in [[Berlin]], Germany, as well as [[Brussels]], Belgium.\n\n== Membership ==\nThe association's membership includes some 70 associations, 250 companies \u2013 ranging from mid-sized firms to international corporations \u2013, as well as 150 organizational and individual members.\n\nThe association itself is a member of the European food industry body [[FoodDrinkEurope]]<ref>[[FoodDrinkEurope]]: [https://www.fooddrinkeurope.eu/member/Lebensmittelverband-Deutschland/ Food Federation Germany (Lebensmittelverband)]</ref> as well as of [[European Movement Germany]].\n\n== History ==\n[[File:Federation for Food Law and Food Science logo.svg|thumb|Federation for Food Law and Food Science logo]]\nFood Federation Germany was founded on March 10, 1955 in [[Nuremberg]], Germany, under the name ''Federation for Food Law and Food Science'' (German: ''Bund f\u00fcr Lebensmittelrecht und Lebensmittelkunde'', abbreviated ''BLL'') as a re-establishment of the ''Federation of German Food Manufacturers and Traders'' (German: ''Bund Deutscher Nahrungsmittel-Fabrikanten und -H\u00e4ndler'') that had been active from 1901 to 1945.<ref>Food Federation Germany: ''[https://www.lebensmittelverband.de/de/verband/historie History]'' (in German).</ref> In May 2019, the association's general meeting voted for changeing the association's name to ''Food Federation Germany'' (German: ''Lebensmittelverband Deutschland'').<ref>Food Federation Germany (9 May 2019): [https://www.lebensmittelverband.de/en/news/20190509-philipp-hengstenberg-is-president-of-new-food-federation-germany Philipp Hengstenberg is president of new \"Food Federation Germany\"]''</ref> The name change came into force in July 2019, followed by a rebranding process that was awarded a ''Rebrand 100: merit'' at the ''2020 Rebrand 100 Global Awards''.<ref>Rebrand.com: [https://rebrand.com/merit-food-federation-germany/ Food Federation Germany. 2020 REBRAND 100: merit].''</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* [https://www.lebensmittelverband.de/en/ Food Federation Germany's English website]\n\n[[Category:Food industry trade groups]]\n[[Category:1955 establishments in Germany]]\n", "name_user": "Benstown", "label": "safe", "comment": "logo size", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Food_Federation_Germany"}
