{"title_page": "Daytime Friends", "text_new": "{{Infobox album\n| name       = Daytime Friends\n| type       = studio\n| artist     = [[Kenny Rogers]]\n| cover      = Daytime friends.jpg\n| alt        =\n| released   = July 1977<ref name=\"lp discography\">{{cite web |url=http://www.lpdiscography.com/?page=main#?page=discography&interpret=316 |title=LP Discography: Kenny Rogers |author= |date= |work= |publisher=LP Discography |accessdate=June 11, 2011}}</ref>\n| recorded   = {{Start date|1977}}\n| venue      =\n| studio     =\n| genre      =\n| length     = 36:33\n| label      = [[United Artists Records|United Artists]]\n| producer   = [[Larry Butler (producer)|Larry Butler]]\n| prev_title = [[Kenny Rogers (album)|Kenny Rogers]]\n| prev_year  = 1977\n| next_title = [[Ten Years of Gold]]\n| next_year  = 1978\n| misc       = {{Singles\n | name      = Kenny Rogers\n | type      = studio\n | single1   = [[Daytime Friends (song)|Daytime Friends]]\n | single1date = August 1, 1977\n | single2   = [[Sweet Music Man]]\n | single2date = October 10, 1977\n}}\n}}\n\n'''''Daytime Friends''''' is the third studio album by [[Kenny Rogers]] for [[United Artists Records]], released worldwide in 1977. It was his second major success following the break-up of [[The First Edition (band)|The First Edition]] in 1976 (his first album ''[[Love Lifted Me]]'' was a minor success, with his second, the self-titled [[Kenny Rogers (1977 album)|''Kenny Rogers'']], going to Number 1 on the US country charts and crossing over to the mainstream pop charts in many countries).\n\nThe album produced two top 10 singles with the title cut reaching No. 1 on the country singles and tracks chart (and the top 40 in the UK pop charts) and \"Sweet Music Man\" (Rogers' own composition) reaching No. 9.<ref name=\"whitburn\">{{cite book|last=Whitburn|first=Joel|title=Hot Country Songs 1944 to 2008|publisher=Record Research, Inc|date=2008|page=360|isbn=0-89820-177-2}}</ref> Elsewhere on the album is a song called \"Am I Too Late\" which was not released as a single, despite Rogers later saying it was one of his favorite songs [https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=7wtNYLVCxwU]. Another track \"My World Begins and Ends With You\" was later recorded by [[Dave & Sugar]], who had a hit single with it in 1979.\n\nThe album reached No. 2 on the Country charts.\n\n==Track listing==\n{{tracklist \n|title1 = [[Daytime Friends (song)|Daytime Friends]]\n|writer1 = [[Ben Peters]]\n|length1 = 3:10\n|title2 = [[Desperado (Eagles song)|Desperado]]\n|writer2 = [[Don Henley]], [[Glenn Frey]]\n|length2 = 3:44\n|title3 = Rock and Roll Man\n|writer3 = [[Kenny O'Dell]]\n|length3 = 2:46\n|title4 = Lying Again\n|writer4 = [[Chips Moman]], [[Larry Butler (producer)|Larry Butler]]\n|length4 = 2:41\n|title5 = I'll Just Write My Music and Sing My Songs\n|writer5 = Thomas Cain\n|length5 = 2:55\n|title6 = My World Begins and Ends With You\n|writer6 = Larry Keith, Steve Pippin\n|length6 = 2:43\n|title7 = [[Sweet Music Man]]\n|writer7 = Rogers\n|length7 = 4:16\n|title8 = Am I Too Late\n|writer8 = Larry Keith\n|length8 = 3:31\n|title9 = We Don't Make Love Anymore\n|writer9 = Rogers\n|length9 = 3:51\n|title10 = Ghost of Another Man\n|writer10 = Frank Dycus, [[George Richey]], [[Roger Bowling]]\n|length10 = 2:57\n|title11 = Let Me Sing For You\n|writer11 = Casey Kelly, Julie Dodier\n|length11 = 4:39\n}}\n\n==Personnel==\n* Kenny Rogers \u2013 lead vocals\n* Bobby Wood, Charles Cochran, Edgar Struble, Gene Golden, [[Hargus \"Pig\" Robbins]], Steve Glassmeyer \u2013 keyboards\n* [[Shane Keister]] \u2013 [[Moog synthesizer]]\n* Billy Sanford, Dave Kirby, Jerry Shook, Jimmy Capps, Jim Colvard, Johnny Christopher, Larry Keith, [[Reggie Young]], T.G. Engel \u2013 guitars\n* [[Pete Drake]] \u2013 steel guitar\n* [[Joe Osborn]], Mike Leech \u2013 bass guitar\n* [[Tommy Allsup]] \u2013 six-string bass guitar\n* [[Bob Moore]] \u2013 upright bass\n* Bobby Daniels, [[Jerry Carrigan]], [[Kenny Malone]] \u2013 drums\n* Brenton Banks, Byron Theodore Bach, Carl Gorodetzky, Gary Vanosdale, George Binkley, Lennie Haight, Marvin Chantry, Pamela Sixfin, Roy Christensen, [[Sheldon Kurland]], Stephanie Woolf, Steven Maxwell Smith, Wilfred Lehmann \u2013 strings\n* [[Bill Justis]] \u2013 string arrangements\n* Bergen White, Bobby Daniels, Buzz Cason, Don Gant, Gene Golden, Johnny MacCrae, [[The Jordanaires]], Larry Keith, Randy Rogers, Sandy Rogers, Steve Glassmeyer, Steve Pippin \u2013 background vocals\n\n==Production==\n* Producer \u2013 Larry Butler\n* Engineers \u2013 Harold Lee and [[Billy Sherrill]]\n* Remix \u2013 Billy Sherrill\n* Recorded at American Studios and [[Jack Clement|Jack Clement Recording Studios]] (Nashville, TN).\n* Mastered by Bob Sowell at Master Control (Nashville, TN).\n* Art Direction \u2013 Ria Lewerke\n* Design \u2013 Bill Burks\n* Photography \u2013 Gary Regester\n* Management \u2013 Ken Kragen\n\n==Westlife version==\n[[Irish people|Irish]] pop band [[Westlife]] recorded it in 2002 with a live performance of it. They renamed it also to \"Daytime Friends, Nighttime Lovers\".\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n{{Kenny Rogers}}\n\n[[Category:Kenny Rogers albums]]\n[[Category:1977 albums]]\n[[Category:United Artists Records albums]]\n[[Category:Albums arranged by Bill Justis]]\n[[Category:Albums produced by Larry Butler (producer)]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox album\n| name       = Daytime Friends\n| type       = studio\n| artist     = [[Kenny Rogers]]\n| cover      = Daytime friends.jpg\n| alt        =\n| released   = July 1977<ref name=\"lp discography\">{{cite web |url=http://www.lpdiscography.com/?page=main#?page=discography&interpret=316 |title=LP Discography: Kenny Rogers |author= |date= |work= |publisher=LP Discography |accessdate=June 11, 2011}}</ref>\n| recorded   = {{Start date|1977}}\n| venue      =\n| studio     =\n| genre      =\n| length     = 36:33\n| label      = [[United Artists Records|United Artists]]\n| producer   = [[Larry Butler (producer)|Larry Butler]]\n| prev_title = [[Kenny Rogers (album)|Kenny Rogers]]\n| prev_year  = 1977\n| next_title = [[Ten Years of Gold]]\n| next_year  = 1978\n| misc       = {{Singles\n | name      = Kenny Rogers\n | type      = studio\n | single1   = [[Daytime Friends (song)|Daytime Friends]]\n | single1date = August 1, 1977\n | single2   = [[Sweet Music Man]]\n | single2date = October 10, 1977\n}}\n}}\n\n'''''Daytime Friends''''' is the third studio album by [[Kenny Rogers]] for [[United Artists Records]], released worldwide in 1977. It was his second major success following the break-up of [[The First Edition (band)|The First Edition]] in 1976 (his first album ''[[Love Lifted Me]]'' was a minor success, with his second, the self-titled [[Kenny Rogers (1977 album)|''Kenny Rogers'']], going to Number 1 on the US country charts and crossing over to the mainstream pop charts in many countries).\n\nThe album produced two top 10 singles with the title cut reaching #1 on the country singles and tracks chart (and the top 40 in the UK pop charts) and \"Sweet Music Man\" (Rogers' own composition) reaching #9.<ref name=\"whitburn\">{{cite book|last=Whitburn|first=Joel|title=Hot Country Songs 1944 to 2008|publisher=Record Research, Inc|date=2008|page=360|isbn=0-89820-177-2}}</ref> Elsewhere on the album is a song called \"Am I Too Late\" which was not released as a single, despite Rogers later saying it was one of his favorite songs [https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=7wtNYLVCxwU]. Another track \"My World Begins and Ends With You\" was later recorded by [[Dave & Sugar]], who had a hit single with it in 1979.\n\nThe album reached #2 on the Country charts.\n\n==Track listing==\n{{tracklist \n|title1 = [[Daytime Friends (song)|Daytime Friends]]\n|writer1 = [[Ben Peters]]\n|length1 = 3:10\n|title2 = [[Desperado (Eagles song)|Desperado]]\n|writer2 = [[Don Henley]], [[Glenn Frey]]\n|length2 = 3:44\n|title3 = Rock and Roll Man\n|writer3 = [[Kenny O'Dell]]\n|length3 = 2:46\n|title4 = Lying Again\n|writer4 = [[Chips Moman]], [[Larry Butler (producer)|Larry Butler]]\n|length4 = 2:41\n|title5 = I'll Just Write My Music and Sing My Songs\n|writer5 = Thomas Cain\n|length5 = 2:55\n|title6 = My World Begins and Ends With You\n|writer6 = Larry Keith, Steve Pippin\n|length6 = 2:43\n|title7 = [[Sweet Music Man]]\n|writer7 = Rogers\n|length7 = 4:16\n|title8 = Am I Too Late\n|writer8 = Larry Keith\n|length8 = 3:31\n|title9 = We Don't Make Love Anymore\n|writer9 = Rogers\n|length9 = 3:51\n|title10 = Ghost of Another Man\n|writer10 = Frank Dycus, [[George Richey]], [[Roger Bowling]]\n|length10 = 2:57\n|title11 = Let Me Sing For You\n|writer11 = Casey Kelly, Julie Dodier\n|length11 = 4:39\n}}\n\n==Personnel==\n* Kenny Rogers \u2013 lead vocals\n* Bobby Wood, Charles Cochran, Edgar Struble, Gene Golden, [[Hargus \"Pig\" Robbins]], Steve Glassmeyer \u2013 keyboards\n* [[Shane Keister]] \u2013 [[Moog synthesizer]]\n* Billy Sanford, Dave Kirby, Jerry Shook, Jimmy Capps, Jim Colvard, Johnny Christopher, Larry Keith, [[Reggie Young]], T.G. Engel \u2013 guitars\n* [[Pete Drake]] \u2013 steel guitar\n* [[Joe Osborn]], Mike Leech \u2013 bass guitar\n* [[Tommy Allsup]] \u2013 six-string bass guitar\n* [[Bob Moore]] \u2013 upright bass\n* Bobby Daniels, [[Jerry Carrigan]], [[Kenny Malone]] \u2013 drums\n* Brenton Banks, Byron Theodore Bach, Carl Gorodetzky, Gary Vanosdale, George Binkley, Lennie Haight, Marvin Chantry, Pamela Sixfin, Roy Christensen, [[Sheldon Kurland]], Stephanie Woolf, Steven Maxwell Smith, Wilfred Lehmann \u2013 strings\n* [[Bill Justis]] \u2013 string arrangements\n* Bergen White, Bobby Daniels, Buzz Cason, Don Gant, Gene Golden, Johnny MacCrae, [[The Jordanaires]], Larry Keith, Randy Rogers, Sandy Rogers, Steve Glassmeyer, Steve Pippin \u2013 background vocals\n\n==Production==\n* Producer \u2013 Larry Butler\n* Engineers \u2013 Harold Lee and [[Billy Sherrill]]\n* Remix \u2013 Billy Sherrill\n* Recorded at American Studios and [[Jack Clement|Jack Clement Recording Studios]] (Nashville, TN).\n* Mastered by Bob Sowell at Master Control (Nashville, TN).\n* Art Direction \u2013 Ria Lewerke\n* Design \u2013 Bill Burks\n* Photography \u2013 Gary Regester\n* Management \u2013 Ken Kragen\n\n==Westlife version==\n[[Irish people|Irish]] pop band [[Westlife]] recorded it in 2002 with a live performance of it. They renamed it also to \"Daytime Friends, Nighttime Lovers\".\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n{{Kenny Rogers}}\n\n[[Category:Kenny Rogers albums]]\n[[Category:1977 albums]]\n[[Category:United Artists Records albums]]\n[[Category:Albums arranged by Bill Justis]]\n[[Category:Albums produced by Larry Butler (producer)]]\n", "name_user": "Kaltenmeyer", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200etop:clean up, replaced: reached # \u2192 reached No.", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Daytime_Friends"}
{"title_page": "Jeannie Seely discography", "text_new": "{{Infobox artist discography\n| Artist          = [[Jeannie Seely]]\n| Image           = Jeannie Seely on Grand Ole Opry.jpg\n| Caption         = Jeannie Seely at the [[Grand Ole Opry]], 2015.\n| Studio          = 16\n| Live            = 1\n| Compilation     = 3\n| Music videos    = 1\n| Singles         = 33\n| Option          = 10\n| Option name     = Other album appearances\n}}\nThe [[Discography|discography]] of American [[country music|country]] artist [[Jeannie Seely]] contains 16 [[studio album]]s, three [[compilation album]]s and 33 [[single (music)|singles]]. Releasing several singles for the [[Challenge Records (1950s-60s label)|Challenge]] label, she moved to [[Nashville, Tennessee]] and signed with [[Monument Records]] in 1966.<ref name=\"Allmusic Bio\">{{cite web |last1=Huey |first1=Steve |title=Jeannie Seely: Biography & History |url=https://www.allmusic.com/artist/jeannie-seely-mn0000234004/biography |website=[[Allmusic]] |accessdate=29 March 2020}}</ref> Releasing \"[[Don't Touch Me]]\" as a single, it became a major hit, reaching number 2 on the ''[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]'' [[Hot Country Songs|Hot Country Singles]] chart.<ref>{{cite web |title=\"Don't Touch Me\" chart history: Country Songs |url=https://www.billboard.com/music/jeannie-seely/chart-history/CSI/song/573335 |website=[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]] |accessdate=29 March 2020}}</ref> It also became her only single to reach the [[Billboard Hot 100]], peaking at number 85.<ref>{{cite web |title=\"Don't Touch Me\" chart history: Hot 100 |url=https://www.billboard.com/music/jeannie-seely/chart-history/HSI/song/573335 |website=[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]] |accessdate=29 March 2020}}</ref> The success led to the release of her debut studio album entitled ''[[The Seely Style]]'', which reached number 8 on the ''Billboard'' [[Top Country Albums]] chart.<ref>{{cite web |title=''The Seely Style'' chart history |url=https://www.billboard.com/music/jeannie-seely/chart-history/CLP/song/832439 |website=[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]] |accessdate=29 March 2020}}</ref>\n\nSeely had several more major hits during the 1960s: \"[[It's Only Love (Jeannie Seely song)|It's Only Love]]\" (1966), \"[[A Wanderin' Man]]\" (1967) and \"[[I'll Love You More (Than You'll Need)]]\" (1968).<ref name=\"Allmusic Bio\"/> She also released three more studio albums during this time. This included ''[[Thanks, Hank!]]'', which peaked at number 17 on the country albums chart in 1967.<ref>{{cite web |title=''Thanks, Hank!'' chart history |url=https://www.billboard.com/music/jeannie-seely/chart-history/CLP/song/832310 |website=[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]] |accessdate=29 March 2020}}</ref> Leaving Monument, Seely signed with [[Decca Records]] and paired with country artist [[Jack Greene]] for a series of duet recordings. Their first single, \"Wish I Didn't Have to Miss You\" (1969), reached number 2 on the ''Billboard'' country chart. Spawning an album,<ref name=\"Allmusic Bio\"/> the project peaked at number 18 on the country albums chart in 1970.<ref>{{cite web |title=''Jack Greene & Jeannie Seely'' chart history |url=https://www.billboard.com/music/jack-greene/chart-history/CLP/song/831852 |website=[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]] |accessdate=29 March 2020}}</ref> After a series of singles and two albums, Seely released two major hits in 1973: \"[[Can I Sleep in Your Arms]]\" and \"[[Lucky Ladies]]\".<ref name=\"Allmusic Bio\"/> The success prompted the release of an album of the same name, which peaked at number 15 on the country albums chart.<ref>{{cite web |title=''Can I Sleep in Your Arms/Lucky Ladies'' chart history |url=https://www.billboard.com/music/jeannie-seely/chart-history/CLP/song/831427 |website=[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]] |accessdate=29 March 2020}}</ref>\n\nSeely continued recording for major labels until the end of the 1970s. Her final singles on [[Columbia Records]] became minor hits on the ''Billboard'' country chart. Her final chart appearance was 1978's \"Take Me to Bed\", which reached number 97.<ref>{{cite web |title=\"Take Me to Bed\" chart history |url=https://www.billboard.com/music/jeannie-seely/chart-history/CSI/song/363176 |website=[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]] |accessdate=29 March 2020}}</ref> Although still touring and performing, she did not release further studio albums again until the 1990s.<ref name=\"Allmusic Bio\"/> Among the highlights of her later material is 2003's ''Life's Highway'', an album of [[bluegrass music|bluegrass]] material.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Lupton |first1=John |title=Jeannie Seely travels life's highways |url=https://www.countrystandardtime.com/d/article.asp?xid=734 |website=Country Standard Time |accessdate=31 March 2020}}</ref> She also issued album of classic country in 2011 entitled ''Vintage Country''. Her most recent release was in 2017 via Cheyenne Records, ''[[Written in Song]]''.<ref name=\"Allmusic Bio\"/>\n\n==Albums==\n===Studio albums===\n{| class=\"wikitable plainrowheaders\" style=\"text-align:center;\"\n|+ List of studio albums, with selected chart positions, and other relevant details\n! scope=\"col\" rowspan=\"2\" style=\"width:18em;\"| Title\n! scope=\"col\" rowspan=\"2\" style=\"width:18em;\"| Album details\n! scope=\"col\" colspan=\"1\"| Peak<br />chart<br />positions\n|-\n! scope=\"col\" style=\"width:3em;font-size:90%;\"|[[Top Country Albums|{{Small|US Country}}]]<br /><ref>{{cite web |title=Jeannie Seely chart history: Country Albums |url=https://www.billboard.com/music/jeannie-seely/chart-history/CLP |website=[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]] |accessdate=30 March 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=Jack Greene chart history: Country Albums |url=https://www.billboard.com/music/jack-greene/chart-history/CLP |website=[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]] |accessdate=30 March 2020}}</ref>\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| ''[[The Seely Style]]''\n|\n* Released: September 1966\n* Label: [[Monument Records|Monument]]\n* Formats: [[Gramophone record|LP]]\n| 8\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| ''[[Thanks, Hank!]]''\n|\n* Released: March 1967\n* Label: Monument\n* Formats: LP\n| 17\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| ''[[I'll Love You More]]''\n|\n* Released: February 1968\n* Label: Monument\n* Formats: LP\n| 30\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| ''[[Little Things (Jeannie Seely album)|Little Things]]''\n|\n* Released: December 1968\n* Label: Monument\n* Formats: LP\n| 36\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| ''[[Jeannie Seely (1969 album)|Jeannie Seely]]''\n|\n* Released: April 1969\n* Label: [[Decca Records|Decca]]\n* Formats: LP\n| \u2014    \n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| ''Jack Greene, Jeannie Seely''<br />{{Small|(with [[Jack Greene]])}}\n|\n* Released: January 1970\n* Label: Decca\n* Formats: LP\n| 18\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| ''Please Be My New Love''\n|\n* Released: August 1970<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Seely |first1=Jeannie |title=''Please Be My New Love'' (LP album) |journal=[[Decca Records]] |date=August 1970}}</ref>\n* Label: Decca\n* Formats: LP\n| \u2014 \n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| ''Two for the Show''<br />{{Small|(with Jack Greene)}}\n|\n* Released: December 1972\n* Label: Decca\n* Formats: LP\n| 36\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| ''Can I Sleep in Your Arms/Lucky Ladies''\n|\n* Released: November 1973\n* Label: [[MCA Records|MCA]]\n* Formats: LP\n| 15\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| ''Jeannie Seely''\n|\n* Released: 1990<ref>{{cite book |last1=Seely |first1=Jeannie |title=''Jeannie Seely'' (cassette album) |date=1990 |publisher=Jeannie Seely}}</ref>\n* Label: Jeannie Seely\n* Formats: [[Audio cassette|Cassette]]\n| \u2014   \n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| ''Number One Christmas''\n|\n* Released: 1994<ref>{{cite web |title=''Number One Christmas'': Jeannie Seely: Songs, Reviews, Credits |url=https://www.allmusic.com/album/number-one-christmas-mw0000895262 |website=[[Allmusic]] |accessdate=31 March 2020}}</ref>\n* Label: Power Pak \n* Formats: Cassette, [[compact disc|CD]]\n| \u2014 \n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| ''Been There...Sung That''\n|\n* Released: 1999<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Seely |first1=Jeannie |title=''Been There, Sung That'' |journal=Shapoke Records |date=1999}}</ref>\n* Label: Shadpoke\n* Formats: Cassette, CD\n| \u2014 \n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| ''Life's Highway''\n|\n* Released: December 9, 2003<ref>{{cite web |title=''Life's Highway'': Jeannie Seely: Songs, Reviews, Credits |url=https://www.allmusic.com/album/lifes-highway-mw0000331444 |website=[[Allmusic]] |accessdate=31 March 2020}}</ref>\n* Label: OMS \n* Formats: CD\n| \u2014 \n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| ''Vintage Country: Old But Treasured''\n|\n* Released: February 1, 2011<ref name=\"Allmusic Bio\"/>\n* Label: Cheyenne \n* Formats: CD\n| \u2014 \n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| ''[[Written in Song]]''\n|\n* Released: January 13, 2017\n* Label: Cheyenne\n* Formats: CD, [[music download]]\n| \u2014 \n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| ''An American Classic''\n|\n* Released: June 5, 2020<ref>{{cite web |title=LMU Honors Jeannie Seely With Honorary Doctorate of Arts Degree |url=https://www.musicconnection.com/lmu-honors-jeannie-seely-honorary-doctorate-arts-degree/ |website=Music Connection |accessdate=30 March 2020}}</ref>\n* Label: [[Curb Records|Curb]]\n* Formats: CD, music download\n| {{tba}}\n|-\n| colspan=\"3\" style=\"font-size:90%\"| \"\u2014\" denotes a recording that did not chart or was not released in that territory.\n|}\n\n=== Live albums ===\n{| class=\"wikitable plainrowheaders\" style=\"text-align:center;\" \n|+ List of albums, showing relevant details\n! scope=\"col\" style=\"width:18em;\"| Title\n! scope=\"col\" style=\"width:18em;\"| Album details\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| ''Live at the Grand Ole Opry''<br/><span style=\"font-size:85%;\">(with Jack Greene)</span>\n| \n* Released: 1978<ref>{{cite web |title=''Live at The Grand Ole Opry'' |url=https://www.discogs.com/Jack-Greene-Jeannie-Seely-Live-At-The-Grand-Ole-Opry/master/1611236 |website=[[Discogs]] |accessdate=31 March 2020}}</ref>\n* Labels: Kardina Records/[[Pinnacle Records|Pinnacle]]\n* Formats: LP, cassette\n|-\n|}\n\n=== Compilation albums ===\n{| class=\"wikitable plainrowheaders\" style=\"text-align:center;\" \n|+ List of albums, showing relevant details\n! scope=\"col\" style=\"width:18em;\"| Title\n! scope=\"col\" style=\"width:18em;\"| Album details\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| ''Make the World Go Away''\n|\n* Released: March 1972<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Seely |first1=Jeannie |title=''Make the World Go Away'' (1972 LP) |journal=[[Decca Records]] |date=March 1972}}</ref>\n* Label: Decca Records\n* Formats: LP\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| ''Greatest Hits''<br/><span style=\"font-size:85%;\">(with Jack Greene)</span>\n| \n* Released: 1982<ref>{{cite web |title=Jack Greene, Jeannie Seely - ''Greatest Hits'' (1982, Vinyl) |url=https://www.discogs.com/Jack-Greene-Jeannie-Seely-Greatest-Hits/release/7356267 |website=[[Discogs]] |accessdate=31 March 2020}}</ref>\n* Label: [[Gusto Records|Gusto]]\n* Formats: Cassette, LP\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| ''Greatest Hits on Monument''<ref>{{cite web |title=''Greatest Hits on Monument'': Jeannie Seely: Songs, Reviews Credits |url=https://www.allmusic.com/album/greatest-hits-on-monument-mw0000094907 |website=[[Allmusic]] |accessdate=31 March 2020}}</ref>\n| \n* Released: March 9, 1993\n* Label: [[Sony Music Entertainment|Sony]]\n* Formats: Cassette, CD\n|-\n|}\n\n== Singles ==\n{| class=\"wikitable plainrowheaders\" style=\"text-align:center;\" border=\"1\"\n|+ List of singles, with selected chart positions, showing other relevant details\n! scope=\"col\" rowspan=\"2\" style=\"width:20em;\"| Title\n! scope=\"col\" rowspan=\"2\"| Year\n! scope=\"col\" colspan=\"4\"| Peak chart positions\n! scope=\"col\" rowspan=\"2\"| Album\n|-\n! scope=\"col\" style=\"width:2.7em;font-size:90%;\"|[[Billboard Hot 100|US]]<br /><ref>{{cite web |title=Jeannie Seely chart history: Hot 100 |url=https://www.billboard.com/music/jeannie-seely/chart-history/HSI |website=[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]] |accessdate=30 March 2020}}</ref>\n! scope=\"col\" style=\"width:2.7em;font-size:90%;\"|[[Hot Country Songs|US<br />{{Small|Country}}]]<br /><ref>{{cite web |title=Jeannie Seely Chart History: Country Songs |url=https://www.billboard.com/music/jeannie-seely/chart-history/CSI |website=[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]] |accessdate=30 March 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=Jack Greene chart history: Country Songs |url=https://www.billboard.com/music/jack-greene/chart-history/country-songs/2 |website=[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]] |accessdate=30 March 2020}}</ref>\n! scope=\"col\" style=\"width:2.7em;font-size:90%;\"|[[Adult Contemporary (chart)|US<br />AC]]<br /><ref>{{cite web |title=Jeannie Seely chart history: Adult Contemporary |url=https://www.billboard.com/music/jeannie-seely/chart-history/ASI |website=[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]] |accessdate=30 March 2020}}</ref>\n! scope=\"col\" style=\"width:2.7em;font-size:90%;\"|[[RPM (magazine)|CAN<br />{{Small|Country}}]]<br /><ref name=cancountry>{{cite magazine|title=Search results for \"Jeannie Seely\" under Country Singles|url=http://www.collectionscanada.gc.ca/rpm/028020-110.01-e.php?PHPSESSID=5cc1co3unir7jujspt8uvvkh86&q1=Jeannie+Seely&q2=Country+Singles&interval=20|magazine=[[RPM (magazine)|RPM]]|accessdate=24 April 2012|date=|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150402142234/http://www.collectionscanada.gc.ca/rpm/028020-110.01-e.php?PHPSESSID=5cc1co3unir7jujspt8uvvkh86&q1=Jeannie+Seely&q2=Country+Singles&interval=20|archive-date=2 April 2015|url-status=dead}}</ref> \n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| \"If I Can't Have You\"<ref name=\"whitburn\">{{cite book|last=Whitburn|first=Joel|title=Hot Country Songs 1944 to 2008|publisher=Record Research, Inc.|year=2008|isbn=0-89820-177-2}}</ref>\n| 1964\n| \u2014 || \u2014 || \u2014 || \u2014\n| {{n/a}}\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| \"Bring It on Back\"<ref name=\"whitburn\"/>\n| rowspan=\"2\"| 1965\n| \u2014 || \u2014 || \u2014 || \u2014\n| {{n/a}}\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| \"Today Is Not the Day\"<ref name=\"whitburn\"/>\n| \u2014 || \u2014 